ce:section.ce:para:
The value of the adsorption isotherms is heavily used to estimate the adsorption method's suitability. So, the adsorption data were applied to the three adsorption models to find the greatest adsorption capacity of E120 adsorption on MMNPs and to explain the adsorption process mechanism. The adsorption isotherms of the Langmuir, Freundlich, and Temkin models were studied using linear forms, as shown in (Fig. S5). Table 1 identified that the Langmuir model was the best fit model for E120 adsorption on MMNPs, which is consistent with the highest correlation coefficient (R2). This confirmed that E120 dye adsorption occurred at the MMNPs surface active sites via H-bond formation (i.e. supposing identical adsorption venues), once the E120 dyeoccupied the sites, no further adsorption could occur. The calculated maximum adsorption capacity (
q m
) by the Langmuir model was found to be 87.7 mg.g−1.
